<TEXT>
president corazon aquino approved 
legal measures friday to block the return of ferdinand marcos who 
has asked a court to grant him permission to come home and face an 
accuser 
at a meeting with key legal advisers she authorized 
solicitorgeneral francisco chavez to file a motion with the 
anticorruption court to reject marcos petition to come home when 
a former cabinet minister gives a deposition against him in 
november 
chavez said that if the lower tribunal upholds marcos request 
the government will appeal to the supreme court to keep the former 
president from coming home from hawaii where he fled after a 
february 1986 uprising that toppled his administration and 
propelled mrs aquino to power 
in a petition filed wednesday with the anticorruption court 
marcos asked permission to return so he could defend himself when 
baltazar aquino the former public works minister gives a 
deposition on alleged kickbacks by japanese firms during the marcos 
administration 
the former minister is not related to the president 
the antigraft court said last week that marcos had the right to 
be present and crossexamine aquino if the testimony was to be used 
in criminal proceedings 
the anticorruption court stopped short of ordering marcos to 
return however and chavez indicated the government will use all 
legal means to prevent marcos from coming to the philippines 
in hawaii marcos spokesman gemmo trinidad withheld comment on 
the governments plans because we are confused by all the 
reports on the proceedings 
aquino presidential spokesman teodoro benigno said the 
government was trying to reconcile the demands of the judiciary 
and the demands of national security 
mrs aquino cited national security as the main reason for 
preventing marcos from coming back from his exile in hawaii 
but she has also pledged to abide by the decision of the courts 
even if they order marcos home 
promarcos groups within the armed forces have been responsible 
for at least two of the half dozen major coup attempts against the 
aquino government key leaders of those coup attempts remain at 
large 
philippine law bans trials in absentia and the government has 
delayed filing charges against marcos for fear he would demand the 
right to return 
the government claims marcos embezzled up to 10 billion during 
his administration efforts to recover the money have foundered in 
large part because of the reluctance to file criminal charges 
</TEXT>
