a colony of more than 2000 bats has 
chased a couple from their home of 15 years and one of them says 
its too scary to move back until theyre sure the winged 
invaders are gone 
after dark each day lorraine and steve disburger watch brown 
bats flutter in and out of the yellow woodframe house they said 
they havent been able to find anyone to help them solve their 
problem largely because they have trouble getting people to 
believe them 
ill never forget the night we left mrs disburger said 
recently i couldnt sleep i was too scared you could hear 
them it was one of those hot nights and it was like the house was 
breathing 
we had the lights on bright she said the bats were right 
in the next room then one lit on steves leg that did it we went 
outside and slept the rest of the night in our camper the next 
morning i begged my motherinlaw to take us in 
that was july 15 and they havent been back to their central 
new york home since except to do laundry and grab a few possessions 
disburger used heavy plastic to seal off the unfinished 
secondfloor room that seems to be the colonys nursery but his 
wife doesnt want to go near the house if she can help it 
its too scary she said 
she said shes been frustrated in trying to get help from pest 
control experts local and state health officials and legislators 
the disburgers have tried ultrasound mothball crystals and 
smoke bombs to get rid of the bats the only weapon that worked was 
a tennis racquet but smashing a bat creates possible exposure to 
rabies and disease carried by the flying mammals 
on thursday stephen frantz a zoologist with the state health 
departments wadsworth center for laboratories and research who 
specializes in rodent and bat diseases visited the disburger home 
judging from what ive heard its certainly a problem 
frantz said before the visit the large number of bats reported 
is unusual but not rare this year there seems to be more people 
with serious problems 
the couple said they noticed more and more bats starting to 
appear at the house about five years ago theyd disappear in the 
winter but would come back in spring she said 
the disburgers tried their best to plug up their old house 
theyd sit in the camper at night and watch the entrances and exits 
used by the bats disburger had ladders ready all around the 
exterior hed run and get some insulation and plug a hole 
the couple said they expect to spend up to 4000 to rid their 
house of the winged varmints that includes scattering the colony 
plugging all the holes and putting on a new roof 
frantz said he was thinking of sealing up most of the holes in 
the house then installing oneway exits in the remaining ones 
when the bats leave at night to feed he said they wont be able 
