<TEXT>
the iranian envoy took a hard line today at the 
second day of the iraniraq peace talks saying a lasting 
settlement to the prolonged dispute depends on observance of a 1975 
border treaty repudiated by iraq 
the joint facetoface session between foreign ministers was 
temporarily abandoned this morning un secretarygeneral javier 
perez de cuellar said it was difficult for the bitter rivals to 
continue meeting they met instead in separate rooms for about two 
hours 
but in the afternoon the facetoface session was resumed by 
iranian foreign minister ali akbar velayati and iraqi foreign 
minister tariq aziz flanked by their delegations there was no 
immediate word on progress 
however velayati delivered a strong statement after the morning 
session about the validity of the 1975 algiers treaty on iraniraq 
boundaries the issue poses a major stumbling block in the 
negotiations 
emerging from the morning session velayati told reporters 
for reaching this comprehensive just and honorable solution we 
have valid criteria united nations resolution 598 the 
outline plan of the secretarygeneral and the 1975 treaty between 
iran and iraq 
in september 1980 president saddam hussein renounced that 
treaty which gave iran rights to the disputed shattalarab 
waterway and five days later invaded iraq 
the border issue and treaty are considered critical to a peace 
settlement because resolution 598 requires troop withdrawal to 
mutually recognized boundaries iraq now says the boundaries are in 
question 
iraqi officials recently reaffirmed their repudiation of that 
treaty 
earlier in the day perez de cuellar told reporters that 
problems between iran and iraq have lasted centuries and then it 
is not in one afternoon that we can decide 
the session began thursday with a joint session led by the 
secretarygeneral and both sides addressed each other through 
intepreters it was the first facetoface meeting of foreign 
ministers since the persian gulf war began almost eight years ago 
but after two hours the session was suspended and both sides 
met in separate chambers for three more hours with un officials 
meeting them and reporting to perez de cuellar 
the format of separate rooms was continued today un spokesman 
francois giuliani said the secretarygeneral first met separately 
with each minister then the delegations consulted in separate 
rooms he said 
un officials based in another room occasionally visited the 
delegations and perez de cuellar at times met the delegations 
separately 
meanwhile a small group of iraqi kurds and other iraqi 
opposition groups demonstrated outside the building and protested 
