<TEXT>
a federal appeals court today upheld contempt 
fines against the city of yonkers for defying an order to 
desegregate housing but capped the penalties at 1 million a day 
diminishing the threat of bankruptcy 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals also upheld contempt fines 
against the four city councilmen who voted against the 
desegregation plan 
previously us district court judge leonard sand imposed fines 
on the city of 100 that would double daily quickly going into the 
millions and breaking the citys annual budget in less than a month 
in a 39page opinion the appeals court also delayed 
reimposition of the fines for seven days to permit the city to seek 
an appeal before the us supreme court 
yonkers mayor nicholas c wasicsko who favors accepting sands 
order did not immediately return a telephone call today seeking 
comment on the ruling 
under the new timetable if the contempt continues yonkers 
would pay 12800 next friday and would reach the 1millionaday 
cap a week after that at which time the city would have paid more 
than 26 million in all the total would mount by 1 million each 
day after that 
the yonkers budget for the year 337 million would be wiped 
out in about 11 months but the city would face bankruptcy long 
before that a state agency has already taken over the citys 
pursestrings imposing spending restrictions and drafting a 
worstcase plan 
sand also imposed 500aday fines against the four councilmen 
and ordered their eventual jailing if they continued to balk at 
complying with his ruling 
those sanctions were suspended aug 9 when the city and the four 
councilmen appealed to the 2nd circuit if they had not been the 
council members were scheduled to go to jail aug 11 
by aug 9 the city had paid 12700 in fines and each 
councilman had paid 3500 
in upholding the fines against the four councilman the 
threejudge appeals panel said the threat of jail would resume in 
nine days 
the four councilmen had indicated thursday they would again vote 
once again to defy the courts at a special city council meeting set 
for 2 pm today 
the defiant council members said they hadnt changed their minds 
about the desegregation plan which would create 800 units of 
affordable housing throughout the city 
sand who in 1985 found yonkers liable for 40 years of 
segregated housing and schooling imposed the fines aug 2 after 
the council refused by a 43 vote to endorse the housing plan 
the city had argued that sands contempt finding and fines were 
unfairly punishing yonkers for the defiance of renegade council 
members who would not change their votes because of the political 
consequences 
lawyers for the council members in turn argued that sand 
exceeded his judicial discretion by ordering members of legislative 
body to vote a certain way 
but the 2nd circuit concluded that under the circumstances of 
this case the recalcitrant council members may be required to vote 
to implement the consent judgment and that the city in addition 
to the council members may be subjected to coercive sanctions 
for failure to abide with sands orders 
the court ruled that sand acted well within his discretion 
in starting the fines against the city at 100 a day but added 
that at some point however the doubling reaches unreasonable 
proportions 
the appeals court noted under the current schedule the fine 
for day 25 is more than 1 billion the fine for day 30 is more 
than 50 billion 
the panel said the doubling fines were excessive when the 
level of each days fine exceeds 1 million 
 
</TEXT>
