<TEXT>
swedes are proud to have sheltered 
political refugees from all over the world but now theyre finding 
their hospitality abused by spies and terrorists officials say 
fifteen or 20 international terrorists may be moving to sweden 
every year to find sanctuary under false identities police say 
they are among thousands of immigrants or refugees seeking asylum 
the many terrorists we have in this country is the price we 
pay for our open society said krister hansen head of the 
antiterrorist section of the security police 
in a recent book titled espionage in sweden several leading 
defense writers claim that neutral sweden is becoming a playground 
in the game of eastwest espionage the soviet kgb keeps about 100 
agents here while the cia has about 10 the book said 
this week swedish police arrested two hungarianborn swedes 
suspected of being couriers for an international spy ring working 
against nato the ring is alleged to be headed by a former american 
army sergeant in west germany 
sandor kercsik 48 and imre kercsik 34 were arraigned in 
court friday prosecutors said they came to sweden in the 1960s 
both doctors they prospered and were wellliked by their 
neighbors who said they were stunned to learn that the brothers 
were agents of the hungarian intelligence service 
in another case this summer police raided the home of a 
palestinian businessman and uncovered documents indicating he was a 
senior commander of the abu nidal terrorist organization 
samir mohammed khadar married a finnishborn swede and moved 
here two years ago he traveled frequently but led an otherwise 
unremarkable life in a stockholm suburb 
in july khadar was blown apart by a bomb in athens the 
explosion was linked to an assault by a terrorist squad a few hours 
later on the city of poros cruise ship which killed nine people and 
wounded about 90 
before leaving on his fatal mission khadar had stashed away a 
supply of weapons in a forest north of stockholm which police said 
could have been used to attack the nearby arlanda international 
airport or an embassy in the city 
hansen told the svenska dagbladet newspaper this week that eight 
of every 10 people seeking political asylum arrive at arlanda 
airport without passports and police cannot be sure who they 
really are 
after years of largescale immigration sweden may have 25000 
residents whose real identities are unknown he said many could be 
common criminals 
it is not generally done to have a security check on 
prospective immigrants said marie andersson of the immigration 
ministry its up to the police to decide 
a newcomer is asked his name and birth date is photographed and 
fingerprinted and within hours can have a new identity 
last year 16000 people came to sweden seeking asylum and 
another 12000 immigrated for other reasons it can take up to two 
years to process the application and during that time the newcomer 
lives at the governments expense 
people like khadar and the kercsik brothers are able to relocate 
in sweden because of a tradition of open doors 
during world war ii sweden accepted jews and other refugees 
fleeing the nazi onslaught later hungarians came after the 1956 
invasion of their country as did czechs after 1968 
independenceseeking kurds fleeing homes in iran or iraq also 
came some belonged to the shadowy kurdish peoples party which had 
been involved in terrorism sweden refused them asylum but did not 
deport them to their native countries where they risked execution 
members of the kurdish group have been suspects in the unsolved 
1986 assassination of swedish prime minister olof palme although 
no one has been prosecuted in the case 
until the 1970s sweden encouraged immigration to fill jobs no 
one talked about terrorism until then ms andersson said in an 
interview 
even when we didnt need the workers any more the legislation 
never changed and the flow of refugees increased she said 
now despite the recent incidents an overhaul of the system is 
unlikely 
everyone is very proud of our generous policy i dont think 
the politicians want to change it said ms andersson 
</TEXT>
