<TEXT>
toyota motor corp sometimes repays dealers who 
make repairs on outofwarranty parts but an executive on friday 
denied that the practice constitutes a secret warranty used to 
quiet customers who complain 
bob daly toyotas national service operations manager 
confirmed information from a 12page toyota document published 
friday in the detroit news that lists 41 components for which 
toyota motor sales usa can be reimbursed by its japanese parent 
company 
the reimbursements let dealers provide free service on the 
components but toyota spokesman jerry giaquinta stressed that the 
list does not set guidelines on what work can be done free of 
charge 
toyota district offices decide what parts will be repaired or 
replaced without charge he said 
the document lists items including cracked dashboard pads 
peeling blue paint slipping automatic transmissions worn engine 
cylinders camshafts cruise controls catalytic converters fuel 
pumps and brakes 
daly said a customer generally has to complain to get the free 
repairs 
a dealer might point out to him that a component shouldnt 
have failed and offer to seek reimbursement from toyota but in 
most cases it would be up to the customer to request it he said 
most automakers long have acknowledged paying for selected 
postwarranty repairs to keep customers satisfied but toyotas 
list apparently is the longest made public the newspaper said 
clarence ditlow director of the center for auto safety a 
public interest group in washington dc called the policy a 
secret warranty used to quiet complaining customers while 
others who do not complain are charged for the same repairs 
what theyre doing is taking care of customers who are likely 
to cause them image problems by squawking too loudly while 
ignoring thousands of others who dont complain ditlow said 
we do not have a secret warranty daly said we make a 
casebycase determination under our customer satisfaction policy 
whether to reimburse for a repair that occurs beyond the normal 
warranty 
</TEXT>
