eight states want to find out whether claims 
made by dozens of food companies in advertising are misleading 
authorities in minnesota california massachusetts new york 
missouri texas iowa and wisconsin are examining advertising that 
could lead consumers to believe that some products are low in such 
substances as cholesterol sugars and fats officials said 
the states have been cooperating in a summerlong investigation 
norine olsonelm a minnesota special assistant attorney general 
said thursday 
we are not challenging ingredients ms olsonelm said from 
her st paul minn office we are concerned about advertising 
and labeling how products are marketed and promoted to the 
public 
the states have not decided how to proceed if they find evidence 
of false or deceptive advertising but they ultimately could sue 
the companies the attorney said 
fines would range from 2500 in california to 25000 in 
minnesota for each violation she said 
the states started the investigation because the claims in some 
of the advertising were not covered by federal law ms olsonelm 
said 
consumers interpret light to mean low in calories rather than 
light in color and texture ms olsonelm said light is not 
defined by federal law consumers have no clear perception other 
than it is a reduction 
five companies known to be under scrutiny are procter amp gamble 
co of cincinnati kitchens of sara lee deerfield ill nabisco 
brands inc east hanover nj campbell soup co camden nj 
and louis rich co madison wis the newspaper said such diverse 
products as soup cereal cheesecake and meats are involved 
procter amp gamble has been asked to provide information 
substantiating its claims that its allvegetable crisco shortening 
contains no cholesterol 
spokesmen for the companies said they stand behind the 
advertising 
the investigation covers television radio and print advertising 
regarding nutrition and such ailments as heart problems cancer and 
osteoporosis 
companies have been asked to provide samples of advertising ms 
olsonelm said 
we have set different deadlines for each company she said 
there is no one target date 
one concern of the states is the use of palm oil which ms 
olsonelm said is higher in saturated fat than many other oils 
although soybean oil is the primary ingredient in pampgs crisco 
shortening advertised as being cholesterolfree it contains 
some palm oil 
studies indicate that saturated fats in palm oil will increase 
cholesterol and therefore we are concerned about palm oil being 
included in products that are otherwise lower in saturated fats 
ms olsonelm said 
cholesterol is a fatty substance in the blood that clogs 
arteries often contributing to heart attacks 
palm oil is added to crisco to give it texture at room 
temperature procter amp gamble spokesman don tassone said 
the saturated fat content of palm oil is 40 percent but because 
of the relatively small amount of it in crisco the overall level 
of saturated fats in crisco is 28 percent tassone said he said 
palm oil as a vegetable oil does not contain cholesterol 
