<DOCNO> AP880826-0289 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
watch your economic assumptions 
this warning could be offered at any time of the year and at any 
point in the economic cycle but it is especially relevant now the 
reason if your assumptions are wrong your conclusions could be 
terribly wrong 
an example of the problem is now circulating in the popular 
media to wit that rising interest rates make it almost inevitable 
that a consumersector recession will develop 
the assumption is that rising rates on variable home mortgage 
loans and other variablerate instruments will cost the consumer 
so much that little will be left for the purchase of goods and 
services 
true rising rates could force many consumers into awkward and 
even destructive financial situations but many others might 
benefit in fact it is likely that more money not less might 
be put into the hands of consumers 
the conclusion that higher rates could ruin the consumer economy 
is based largely on the assumption that there are more debts than 
assets 
not so says e eric heinemann chief economist of the 
investment firm ladenburg thalmann amp co 
he observes that the reverse is true explaining data 
compiled by the federal reserve and the commerce department show 
plainly that during periods of rising rates consumer interest 
income goes up more than consumer interest payments 
the reason for this is simple overall american consumers are 
enormous net creditors their financial assets exceed their debts 
by at least 4 trillion a margin of more than 2 to 1 
another error of assumption might entrap those who argue that 
the economy faces a downturn for the simple reason that the 
economic expansion now in its 69th month is due for a fall it is 
too old they say 
maybe so maybe not 
some economists arent convinced that the economy has been on a 
steady roll for nearly seven years they concede that the official 
figures indicate an uninterrupted expansion but they wonder if the 
figures are correct 
some of the questioning arises from data supplied by sindlinger 
amp co a wallingford pa research firm that obtains its 
information from intensive telephone interviews with a 
crosssection of households 
the key to the consumer economy says albert sindlinger is what 
he calls household liquidity or a continuing measurement of 
the financial ability of households that he says is the engine 
of the economy 
by our calculations based on household liquidity the current 
economic recovery is about 20 months old says sindlinger 
household liquidity he says bottomed out in november 1986 at the 
time he listed 31 states in recession 
he contends this was a genuine recession a bona fide 
interruption of the economic expansion but that it was obscured 
from national figures by unusually strong economic activity on the 
east and west coasts 
sindlinger measures only a few states remaining in recession 
now but asserts that if that wasnt a recession we went through 
two years ago then an unidentified monster was plodding through the 
economic woods 
another incorrect assumption trapped some of the haughtiest 
economic minds last october when so many of them stated flatly 
that a securities market collapse of such great magnitude would 
lead inevitably to recession 
some will continue to argue that in spite of a strong economy 
the verdict isnt in yet that a recession still lies ahead but 
they arent likely to get much of a hearing 
a recession could be in the offing since recessions are always 
in the offing some economists would have nothing to say if that 
threat wasnt there to talk about 
but linking the next recession to the securities market collapse 
is getting more difficult by the day the collapse might indeed by 
a contributant to that recession but it will be difficult to cite 
it as the trigger or chief factor 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

