<DOCNO> AP880826-0313 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a threeyear battle over the seattletokyo air 
route took another twist friday as a federal appeals court ordered 
the department of transportation to award the route now held by 
united airlines to rival continental airlines 
the decision by the us circuit court of appeals for the 
district of columbia left continental joyful united silent and a 
third contender for the route american airlines puzzled 
a transportation department spokesman said the agency would have 
no immediate comment 
the lawyers are studying it and a response will be 
forthcoming the spokesman bill mosley said 
united spokesman joe hopkins in chicago responded we will 
have no comment until we have time to review it 
continental president martin r shugrue said his airline was 
extremely gratified with the decision 
the law was on our side as we maintained all along 
were clearly disappointed said american spokesman jim 
brown in fort worth texas however at this point since we were 
not involved in that particular litigation theres not a great 
deal of action we can take that we are aware of we will look more 
closely at the decision by the appeals court to see if in fact 
american airlines has any options at this point 
its difficult for us to see how continental airlines would be 
a carrier that would help strengthen national interests as it 
regards service to tokyo and transpacific service in general 
continental american and united have been vying for the 
seattletokyo run and at various times each has been recommended by 
administrative law judges or senior dot officials to fly the route 
this summer alone an administrative law judge recommended that 
united be awarded the route a top dot official subsequently 
recommended it go to american and a dot assistant secretary then 
said further study was needed 
the appeals court in a highly technical order ruled dot 
violated administrative procedures when in june 1987 it decided to 
begin again the process of selecting an airline rather than making 
a final decision 
at that time an administrative law judge recommended 
continental be awarded the route but a senior dot official 
disagreed recommending united retain it 
in fridays ruling the appellate court said continental and 
american had a statutory right to a prompt decision on the merits 
of their applications for the route and the department cannot 
escape this obligation 
the court said the dot had had 90 days to either accept the 
administrative law judges recommendation or come up with its own 
decision on who should fly the route starting the proceedings over 
was not acceptable the court said 
the court ordered that dot recommend to president reagan that 
continental receive the route 
mosley said the white house would review the recommendation for 
foreign policy or national defense implications but approval 
was usually proforma 
all three airlines had engaged in a heated competition for the 
route 
united president stephen wolf said at a hearing it would be 
unfair for the department to strip his airline of the route after 
it had spent years trying to acquire it and had sunk millions of 
dollars into developing it at a time when it was just becoming 
profitable 
united had previously warned it would have to cancel its 
seattlehong kong run if it lost the route and transfer many of its 
2500 employees workers based at seattletacoma international 
airport 
american president robert crandall testified that united which 
already flies between los angeles and tokyo and san francisco and 
tokyo wanted to retain the seattle route to block other airlines 
from gaining a foothold in far east markets 
continental chairman frank lorenzo said his airline was prepared 
to slash fares to the far east if it received the route including 
oneway seattletokyo fares as low as 299 
</TEXT>
